{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AgrEwqjtjzQsRkNtrmWZM7","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-2-flow-execution-loop-blocks.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 5-2 (Flow Execution -- Loop Blocks) with 10 acceptance criteria covering loop termination on pass/max-iterations/circuit-breaker, finding injection into retry prompts, failed-story-only filtering, verdict parsing, iteration tracking, error handling, test coverage, and regression safety. All ACs tagged `test-provable` since the entire story operates on in-memory orchestration logic testable via unit tests with mocked dependencies.\n\n6 tasks defined: type definitions, verdict parsing, finding injection, failed-story filtering, loop execution implementation, and unit tests.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:** None. All source files and artifacts were accessible.\n\n**Workarounds applied:** None.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- The `dispatchTask()` function signature needs a backward-compatible change (adding optional `customPrompt` parameter). This is a minor API change that could affect story 5-1's tests if not handled carefully -- noted in Dev Notes.\n- The verdict parsing in this story is deliberately naive (`JSON.parse` only). Full schema validation is deferred to Epic 6 (story 6-2). If the evaluator produces partial/malformed JSON that passes `JSON.parse` but lacks required fields, the engine may behave unexpectedly. The `parseVerdict()` function should check for required top-level fields.\n- The `maxIterations` default of 5 is an assumption from the epic description (\"max iterations\") without a specific number in the PRD. This should be configurable and the default reviewed.\n\n**Observations:**\n- All 10 ACs are `test-provable` -- the loop block is pure orchestration logic with no runtime dependencies. This is ideal for unit testing.\n- Story 5-1 explicitly left `isLoopBlock()` skip logic as a placeholder for this story, making the handoff clean.\n- The architecture places feedback loop logic (FR29-30) inside `workflow-engine` rather than a separate module, which keeps this story self-contained.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 12\n- By tool: Read: 6, Grep: 3, Glob: 3, Bash: 1, Write: 1, other: 0\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `ls implementation-artifacts` (~20 lines)\n- Files read: 8 unique, 8 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: none"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ab109b32e1e997cbe (use SendMessage with to: 'ab109b32e1e997cbe' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 57444\ntool_uses: 22\nduration_ms: 157629</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7447df8e-50f4-441a-b8fe-e85605fee72e","uuid":"b2caf6e8-b167-4630-ab69-3104ce4e3429","timestamp":"2026-04-02T22:16:05.090Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 5-2-flow-execution-loop-blocks. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append a verification tier tag using this decision tree:\n\n**Tier Decision Tree (append one `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag per AC):**\n- `test-provable` — AC can be verified by building the project and running tests/linters/grep. No running app needed. Examples: 'function X exists', 'type Y is exported', 'test Z passes', 'file has <300 lines'.\n- `runtime-provable` — AC requires running the app locally and checking its behavior (CLI output, HTTP response, process lifecycle). No Docker stack needed. Examples: 'CLI prints usage when invoked with --help', 'server responds 200 on /health', 'process exits 0 on valid input'.\n- `environment-provable` — AC requires a full environment (Docker stack, database, observability, multi-service interaction). Examples: 'logs appear in VictoriaLogs', 'metrics are emitted to VictoriaMetrics', 'container communicates with service X'.\n- `escalate` — AC genuinely cannot be automated (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment). This is rare. Examples: 'UI looks correct on mobile', 'payment processes successfully in production'.\n\nDefault to `test-provable` when unsure. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n\nMANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n- Total tool calls: N\n- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls","agentId":"ab109b32e1e997cbe","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-2-flow-execution-loop-blocks.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 5-2 (Flow Execution -- Loop Blocks) with 10 acceptance criteria covering loop termination on pass/max-iterations/circuit-breaker, finding injection into retry prompts, failed-story-only filtering, verdict parsing, iteration tracking, error handling, test coverage, and regression safety. All ACs tagged `test-provable` since the entire story operates on in-memory orchestration logic testable via unit tests with mocked 